		<item>
		<title>How to estimate your linear actuator needs with minimal application data</title>
		<link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/LinearMotionTips/~3/nwb0bY_GMe0/</link>
		<comments>http://www.linearmotiontips.com/how-to-estimate-your-linear-actuator-needs-with-minimal-application-data/#respond</comments>
		<pubDate>Wed, 11 Jan 2017 21:23:39 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Danielle Collins]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Applications]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Featured]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Linear actuators (all)]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.linearmotiontips.com/?p=6115</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[<p>Choosing linear motion components during the developmentÂ phase of a project has been a source of frustration for designers and application engineers for decadesâespecially when it comes to complex subassemblies such as linear actuators. Consider for a moment the influence that a linear actuator has on the overall machine design. First of all, in an actuator, [&#8230;]</p>
<p><a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.linearmotiontips.com">Linear Motion Tips</a></p>
]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Choosing linear motion components during the developmentÂ phase of a project has been a source of frustration for designers and application engineers for decadesâespecially when it comes to complex subassemblies such as linear actuators. Consider for a moment the influence that a linear actuator has on the overall machine design. First of all, in an actuator, the guide and drive are coupled together, integral to the unit. So itâs imperative that Â both the guide selection and the drive selection are correct. Also, an actuator has significant influence on the overall size of the machine. For example,Â shifting the position of the load on the actuatorÂ can cause aÂ high moment load and change the requirement from a single-guide design to a dual-guide design, effectively doubling or tripling the actuatorâs overall width, and hence the size of the machine.</p>
<div id="attachment_4835" style="width: 379px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img class="wp-image-4835" src="http://www.linearmotiontips.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/Rollon-how-to-specify-actuators-integration.jpg" alt="Rollon-how-to-specify-actuators-integration" width="369" height="294" srcset="http://1ugn2l2m3z2y31d4y73c1m5w.wpengine.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/Rollon-how-to-specify-actuators-integration.jpg 500w, http://1ugn2l2m3z2y31d4y73c1m5w.wpengine.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/Rollon-how-to-specify-actuators-integration-300x239.jpg 300w" sizes="(max-width: 369px) 100vw, 369px" /><p class="wp-caption-text">High moment loads can dictate the use of a dual-rail style linear actuator, which can be two or three times wider than a single rail design.<br /><em>Image credit: Rollon Corp.</em></p></div>
<p>SelectingÂ an actuator based on approximations of the performance requirementsÂ is arguably more risky than choosing a linear guide or drive with minimal application info. But still, the situation is quite common where a designer or engineer needs a reasonable estimate of the systemÂ that will work best for their application, before all the application criteria are nailed down.</p>
<p>Although a proper sizing exercise requires a thorough understanding of theÂ application requirements, a general solutionâsuitable for initial design and costing estimatesâcan usually be established based on fourÂ keyÂ criteria.</p>
<hr />
<h4>Load</h4>
<p>The load that needs to be carried, and its orientationÂ relative to the system, is one of the most important criteria in choosing a linear actuator. Light loads that are mounted more-or-less directly over the bearings can be accommodated by virtually any guide technologyârecirculating profiled rail bearings, linear bushings and shafts, or even plain bearings. However, the heavier the load, and the more moment (pitch, roll, and/or yaw) that it creates, the more robust the guide mechanismÂ should be in order to ensure suitable life and minimal deflection.</p>
<h4>Accuracy</h4>
<p>Understanding the requirements for positioning accuracy and repeatability will helpÂ to narrow the decision regarding drive mechanism. Low-accuracy, point-to-point positioning can be accomplished with a pneumatic drive or belt and pulley system, while positioning accuracy and repeatability in the single-micron range would requireÂ a ball screw or even a linear motor. Although the load can often be accommodated by any of several drive technologies,Â repeatability is oftenÂ the deciding factor between these options.</p>
<h4>Speed</h4>
<p>The average and maximum velocities during the move will also help define the choice of drive mechanism. For example, a rule of thumb is that maximum speed for ball screw assemblies is 1 m/s, although there are <a href="http://www.linearmotiontips.com/long-travel-vs-high-speed-part-2/" target="_blank">ways to obtain faster speeds</a>. Belts, on the other hand, can easily travel up to 10 m/s, and maximum speed for linear motor drives is primarily limited by the supporting guide mechanism. Acceleration also plays a role, both in drive and guide selection.</p>
<h4>Travel</h4>
<p>While the required travel is less often a make-or-break criteria, itâs important to double-check that the chosen linear actuator type can meet the specification for stroke length. Ball and lead screws in particular have limited travel ranges. Again, a rule of thumb for screw drives is 3 meters maximum length. Although screws are available in longer lengths, as length increases, maximum speed decreases, due to the <a href="http://www.linearmotiontips.com/achieve-long-travel-high-speed-ball-screws/" target="_blank">critical speed</a> of the screw.</p>
<div id="attachment_6117" style="width: 528px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img class=" wp-image-6117" src="http://www.linearmotiontips.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/Critical-Speed-Chart-Tolomatic-Screw.jpg" alt="linear actuator" width="518" height="316" srcset="http://1ugn2l2m3z2y31d4y73c1m5w.wpengine.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/Critical-Speed-Chart-Tolomatic-Screw.jpg 1837w, http://1ugn2l2m3z2y31d4y73c1m5w.wpengine.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/Critical-Speed-Chart-Tolomatic-Screw-300x183.jpg 300w, http://1ugn2l2m3z2y31d4y73c1m5w.wpengine.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/Critical-Speed-Chart-Tolomatic-Screw-768x468.jpg 768w, http://1ugn2l2m3z2y31d4y73c1m5w.wpengine.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/Critical-Speed-Chart-Tolomatic-Screw-1024x624.jpg 1024w" sizes="(max-width: 518px) 100vw, 518px" /><p class="wp-caption-text">For actuators with ball screw drives, maximum (critical) speed falls sharply beyond a certain stroke length.<br /><em>Image credit: Tolomatic, Inc.</em></p></div>
<hr />
<p>While theseÂ four criteria can provide a ballpark estimate of suitable linear actuators, in order to carry out a complete sizing and selection process, a number of application parametersÂ must be specified and considered. To help designers and engineersÂ gather the critical information needed forÂ sizing, several manufacturers have come up with simple acronyms to follow.</p>
<p><a href="https://www.boschrexroth.com/en/us/products/product-groups/linear-motion-technology/linear-motion-systems/linear-motion-systems-overview/how-to-choose-a-module/index" target="_blank">Bosch Rexroth</a> uses the acronym <strong>LOSTPED</strong> to guide engineers in defining the application requirements for <strong>L</strong>oad, <strong>O</strong>rientation, <strong>S</strong>peed, <strong>T</strong>ravel, <strong>P</strong>recision, <strong>E</strong>nvironment, and <strong>D</strong>uty cycle.</p>
<p>Similarly, <a href="http://www.rollon.com/US/en/news-item/620-how-to-accomplish-predictable--reliable-linear-motion/" target="_blank">Rollon</a> uses the acronym <strong>ACTUATOR</strong>, which stands for <strong>A</strong>ccuracy, <strong>C</strong>apacity, <strong>T</strong>ravel length, <strong>U</strong>sage (aka duty cycle), <strong>A</strong>mbient environment, <strong>T</strong>iming (aka time and budget), <strong>O</strong>rientation, and <strong>R</strong>ates (aka motion profile).</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><em>Feature image credit: Thomson Industries</em></p>
<p><a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.linearmotiontips.com">Linear Motion Tips</a></p>
<img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/LinearMotionTips/~4/nwb0bY_GMe0" height="1" width="1" alt=""/>]]></content:encoded>
