		<title>The top 5.5 linear motion stories of 2016</title>
		<link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/LinearMotionTips/~3/Jwse8gnK9sw/</link>
		<comments>http://www.linearmotiontips.com/top-5-5-linear-motion-stories-2016/#respond</comments>
		<pubDate>Thu, 29 Dec 2016 12:45:24 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Danielle Collins]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Applications]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Featured]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Linear actuators (all)]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Linear drives (all)]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Linear motors]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Slides + guides (all)]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.linearmotiontips.com/?p=6098</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[<p>As a writer and editor, it&#8217;s always fun (and sometimes surprising)Â to look back at the end of the year and see what articles our readers were most interested in. And for you, our readers, it offers the chance to take a quick look at what are, at least to some of your peers, important topics [&#8230;]</p>
<p><a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.linearmotiontips.com">Linear Motion Tips</a></p>
]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>As a writer and editor, it&#8217;s always fun (and sometimes surprising)Â to look back at the end of the year and see what articles our readers were most interested in. And for you, our readers, it offers the chance to take a quick look at what are, at least to some of your peers, important topics in the world of linear motion. With this in mind, here are the top 5 (and one bonus!) <a href="http://www.linearmotiontips.com" target="_blank">LinearMotionTips.com</a> articles of 2016.</p>
<hr />
<h2>1. How to calculate motor drive torque for ball screws</h2>
<hr />
<p><img class="alignright wp-image-5374" src="http://www.linearmotiontips.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/BWC-xla15.jpg" alt="" width="251" height="174" srcset="http://1ugn2l2m3z2y31d4y73c1m5w.wpengine.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/BWC-xla15.jpg 320w, http://1ugn2l2m3z2y31d4y73c1m5w.wpengine.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/BWC-xla15-300x207.jpg 300w" sizes="(max-width: 251px) 100vw, 251px" />When sizing a motor, one of the most important factors is the required torque. In general, motor torque-speed curves outline two primary areas of permissible torque: continuous and intermittent. Intermittent motor torque is allowed only for a short time (specified by the manufacturer) and in most cases is the torque required during acceleration.Â A motorâs continuous torque is determined by calculating theÂ <a href="http://www.linearmotiontips.com/why-rms-torque-is-important-for-motor-sizing/" target="_blank">root mean square</a>Â of all the torques that occur throughout the application, which typically includes torque during acceleration, torque during constant speed, and torque during deceleration.</p>
<p><a href="http://www.linearmotiontips.com/calculate-motor-drive-torque-ball-screws/" target="_blank"><em>Read the full article here.</em></a></p>
<p><a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.linearmotiontips.com">Linear Motion Tips</a></p>
